    <td valign="top" bgcolor="#DDDED0"> 
      <table width="615" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" class="para" align="right">
        <tr> 
          <td height="50" class="title_big" valign="bottom"><!-- #BeginEditable "Page title here" --><font color="#9B9E61">Calendar 

            Terms</font><!-- #EndEditable --></td>
          <td valign="top" class="titles_2" rowspan="2"></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td width="490" valign="top"> <!-- #BeginEditable "insert main text/graphics/links here" --> 

            <p><span class="maintextsubhead"><strong>Masa</strong></span><span class="maintextsubsubhead"><br>

              </span>The first division of the lunar year is the <i>masa</i> or 

              month. The twelve months are named after twelve expansions of Lord 

              Krishna. An extra month, Purusottama Adhika Masa, is added to leap 

              years (approximately every three years).</p>

            <p><span class="maintextsubhead"><strong>Sankranti</strong></span><span class="maintextsubsubhead"><br>

              </span>The twelve signs of the zodiac. The Vedic astrological signs 

              are the same as the Western 'star signs' with one major exception 

              &#151; Western astrology doesn't account for the precession of the 

              equinoxes (the 'wobble' of the Earth's axis). This means that Western 

              astrology assumes the beginning of the zodiac to be about 24&deg; 

              from its actual beginning. The dates on this calendar are calculated 

              for the sidereal, based on the actual position of the planets relative 

              to the constellations.</p>

            <p><span class="maintextsubhead"><strong>Tithi</strong></span><br>

              The lunar month is divided into 30 parts, each called a lunar day 

              or <i>tithi</i>. A <i>tithi</i> varies in length from 19 to 24 hours 

              and may start at any time of the day.</p>

            <p>The first <i>tithi</i> (Pratipat) starts at the moment when the 

              moon is full, and is followed by fourteen more until the new moon. 

              The names of the tithis are the same for the dark-moon fortnight 

              (Krishna-paksha) as they are for the light-moon fortnight (Gaura-paksha), 

              except for the full moon and new moon days (Purnima and Amavasya 

              respectively).</p>

            <p><span class="maintextsubhead"><strong>Nakshatra</strong></span><br>

              As well as the better known system of dividing the zodiac into twelve 

              signs, it can also be divided into 27 equal parts, each covering 

              131/3&deg;. These are known as <i>nakshatras</i>. As the moon passes 

              through the zodiac, it passes through each <i>nakshatra</i> in about 

              one day. <i>Nakshatras</i> are classified in various ways according 

              to presiding demigod, ruling planet, basic attribute, gender, varna, 

              species etc. and can be used to indicate auspicious and inauspicious 

              times for the performance of different activities.</p>

            <p><span class="maintextsubhead"><strong>Yoga</strong></span><br>
              There are also 27 yogas, determined by dividing the sum of the longitude 
              of the sun and moon by 131/3&deg;. </p>
            <p>As with <i>nakshatras</i>, the use of yogas is a specialised topic 
              used by Vaisnavas to determine auspicious times to perform important 
              activities such as marriage, <i>pujas</i>, travel, and changes of 
              <i>asrama</i>.</p>

            <p align="right"><!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/back_top.lbi" -->
